1. Microsoft Software & Platform Architecture
  a. Core Framework: .NET Ecosystem
    b. Built around .NET
      c. Supports multiple languages
        d. C#, F#, VB.NET
  b. Architectural Styles
    a. Monolithic architecture (older enterprise apps)
    b. Layered (N-tier) architecture
      a. Presentation Layer
      b. Business Logic Layer
      c. Data access layer
  c. Microservices architecture
    a. decoupled services communication via APIs
    b. Often deployed in containers
2. Microsoft Cloud Architecture (Azure)
    a. Core Architectural Model
      a. Distributed systems
      b. Elastic scalability 
      c. High availability (multi-region design)
    b. Key components
      a. Compute
        a. Virtual Machines (IaaS)
        b. Azure kubernetes Service (AKS)
        c. Serverless: 
          Azure Fucntions
      b. Storage
        a. Blob storage(unstructured data)
        b. SQL Databae (managed relational DB)
        c. Cosmos DB (NoSQL, globally distributed)
      c. Networking
        a. Virtual Networks (VNets)
        b. Load Balancers
        c. API Gateways
      d. Identity & Security
        a. Azure Active Directory (now Entra ID)
        b. Role-based access control (RBAC)
    a. Cloud Architecture Patterns (Azure-focused)
      a. Microservices + Containers
      b. Event-driven architecture
      c. Serverless architecture
      d. Hybrid architecture
        a. On-prem + Cloud via Azure Arc
3. Microsoft System/OS Architecture
  Windows Architecture
    - Based on Windows NT Kernel
  I. Key Layers
    a. User Mode
      a. Applications
      b. Subsystems (Win32, etc)
    b. Kernel Mode
      a. Executive services
      b. Memory manager
      c. Scheduler
      d. Device drivers
    * This seperation improves: stability, security, and fault isolation
4. Xbox System Architecture (Gaming)
  a. Custom AMD-based SoCs (CPU + GPU integration)
  b. Shared memory architecture (GDDR)
  c. Optimized OS derived from Windows core
  d. DirectX graphics pipline
5. Enterprise Architecture Frameworks
I. Microsoft Application Architecture Guide
  a. Design principles (seperation of concerns, SOLID)
  b. DevOps integraion
  c. Security-first design
II. Integration with Industry Frameworks
  a. TOGAF (enterprise architecture)
  b. Cloud Adoption Framework (CAF)
*Across all domains: 
  a. Scalability - cloud-native design
  b. Modularity - microservices & APIs
  c. Security - zero trust model
  d. Interoperability - cross-platform (.NET Core, REST APIs)
  e. DevOps - CI/CD pipelines (Azure DevOps, GitHub)
* Takeaway Microsoft archtitecture is not a single system- its a stacked ecosystem
  a. .NET + ASP.NET - application architecture
  b. Azure - cloud/distributed architecture
  c. Windows NT - operating system foundation
  d. Xbox + Surface - hardware-integrated systems
